<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>
<!--
    AccessibilityService configuration — Phase 5

    This file tells Android WHAT events our service wants and WHAT capabilities
    it needs. The system reads it at service-bind time to grant the right access.

    android:accessibilityEventTypes
        Which UI events we receive in onAccessibilityEvent().
        typeWindowStateChanged  — fires when a new Activity/Dialog opens. We use
                                  this to reset state when Matiks navigates screens.
        typeWindowContentChanged — fires when any view's content changes (text
                                   updated, view added/removed). This fires after
                                   Matiks renders a new math problem.

        WHY NOT subscribe to everything?
        Each event fires a Binder IPC from the target app's process to ours.
        Subscribing to all event types on all apps would flood our service with
        thousands of events per second. Restricting to these two keeps it quiet.

    android:packageNames
        Restrict events to Matiks only. Our service receives ZERO events from
        any other app — no privacy implications, no performance cost.

        HOW TO FIND THE PACKAGE NAME OF ANY APP:
          1. Install the app and open it.
          2. Run: adb shell dumpsys window windows | grep mCurrentFocus
             Output example: mCurrentFocus=Window{... in.matiks/...}
          3. The segment before "/" is the package name.

        NOTE: If you play Matiks in a browser, change this to the browser's
        package name (e.g. "com.android.chrome"). In that case, canRetrieveWindowContent
        will give you the WebView's accessibility tree instead of a native one.

    android:canRetrieveWindowContent="true"
        Without this, performAction() calls (ACTION_SET_TEXT, ACTION_CLICK) are
        silently ignored. This is the flag that allows reading AND writing to
        another app's window. It's why users see an "Observe and control actions"
        warning when enabling any accessibility service.

    android:accessibilityFlags="flagReportViewIds"
        Tells the system to include android:id resource names in AccessibilityNodeInfo.
        Without this, node.viewIdResourceName is always null — making it impossible
        to find nodes by ID. Useful for debugging with the Layout Inspector.
-->
<accessibility-service xmlns:android="http://schemas.android.com/apk/res/android"
    android:accessibilityEventTypes="typeWindowStateChanged|typeWindowContentChanged"
    android:accessibilityFeedbackType="feedbackGeneric"
    android:accessibilityFlags="flagReportViewIds"
    android:canRetrieveWindowContent="true"
    android:description="@string/accessibility_service_description"
    android:packageNames="in.matiks" />
